 the metadata, but it doesn't seem to. I should validate the metadata schema and ensure type names reflect correctly in JSON. Lastly, I’ll keep coverage organized in dedicated test files.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering serialization and testing**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using a case class in the test to ensure it's Serializable, but then I need to consider the metadata required for the test class instead of the library itself. There’s this dynamic site requirement in line 468, where it gets called for each element. If the list is non-empty, I need to address how to handle empty lists without needing extra checks. I also realized I'll need to ensure streams are closed properly. Perhaps I should add type annotations for better clarity and handle potential type erasure. I'll keep everything structured and organized for clarity!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring alias imports**\\n\\nI’m considering a potential compile issue with the alias import `import scala.collection.immutable.{List => ImmutableList}` in Scala 2.11. It seems like `ImmutableList(\\\"alpha\\\")` is treated as an object, but I wonder if the type alias is defining a class instead. Also, does this import rename the companion object as well? I need to clarify these aspects because they could affect how I use the alias in my code. Understanding this should help ensure everything compiles smoothly!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_tnqxcGs3biybREhGCSuljF9h|fc_0f7aec41d7c0792e0169f9109970d4819191a795e8b645ed27", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "rg -n 'serializable|serialization' docs tests build-logic common -g '*.md' -g '*.java' -g '*.groovy' | head -100", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 361, "output": 973, "cacheRead": 39424, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 40758, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777930379201, "responseId": "resp_0f7aec41d7c0792e0169f9108bc6c081919b7e42c41157fe2a"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_tnqxcGs3biybREhGCSuljF9h|fc_0f7aec41d7c0792e0169f9109970d4819191a795e8b645ed27", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "rg: build-logic: No such file or directory (os error 2)\nrg: common: No such file or directory (os error 2)\ndocs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:13:Reachability metadata describes reflection, JNI, resource access, serialization, and proxy use that GraalVM `native-image` cannot determine through static analysis. By centralizing this metadata, the repository allows libraries that are not yet self-contained for native compilation to \"just work\" with `native-image` when consumed via the GraalVM Gradle and Maven plugins.\ndocs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:139:    NI-->>App: native image with reflection / JNI /<br/>resources / serialization / proxies registered\ndocs/FUNCTIONAL_SPEC.md:165:**3. `<groupId>/<artifactId>/<metadata-version>/reachability-metadata.json`** — the only file the plugin loads at native-image time. Schema [reachability-metadata-schema-v1.2.0.json](../metadata/schemas/reachability-metadata-schema-v1.2.0.json) (a vendored copy of the upstream GraalVM schema), with top-level keys `reflection`, `jni`, `resources`, `bundles`, `serialization`, and `foreignCalls`. Every entry must carry a `condition.typeReachable` clause (FR-M-2) so the plugin can rely on conditional registration. The legacy split-config layout (`reflect-config.json`, `jni-config.json`, …) is no longer present.\ntests/tck-build-logic/src/main/java/org/graalvm/internal/tck/utils/MetadataGenerationUtils.java:99:     * call stack only contains test + JDK frames, e.g. test-driven serialization).\ntests/tck-build-logic/src/main/java/org/graalvm/internal/tck/MetadataFilesCheckerTask.java:172:            containsErrors |= containsDuplicatedEntries(metadata.path(\"serialization\"), \"serialization\", file);\ntests/tck-build-logic/src/